 Hardware Required:
   *  Arduino Board (Any Version)
   *  GPS Module (e.g., NEO-6M or similar)
   *  Cellular Module (e.g., SIM800L or similar)
   *  Power Source (Batteries or Wall Adapter)
   *  Breadboard and Jumper Wires
   *  USB Cable for Arduino

2. Software Required:
   *  Arduino IDE (Latest Version)
   *  Google's TinyGPS++ Library (Latest Version)

3. Hardware Assembly:
   * Connect the GPS module to the Arduino board as follows:
     - VCC pin of the GPS module connects to the 5V pin on the Arduino.
     - GND pin of the GPS module connects to the GND pin on the Arduino.
     - TX pin of the GPS module connects to the RX pin on the Arduino (and vice versa).
   * Connect the cellular module to the Arduino board as follows:
     - VCC pin of the cellular module connects to the 5V pin on the Arduino.
     - GND pin of the cellular module connects to the GND pin on the Arduino.
     - TX pin of the cellular module connects to the RX pin on the Arduino (and vice versa).
   * Power the system using a power source (batteries or wall adapter).

4. Software Setup:
   * Download and install the latest version of the Arduino IDE from the official website.
   * Download and install the TinyGPS++ library from GitHub, following these steps:
     - Create a new directory for your project (e.g., GPS Tracker).
     - Navigate to that directory using your terminal or command prompt.
     - Run the following commands: `git clone https://github.com/mikeobrien/tinygpsplus.git` and then `cd tinygpsplus`.
     - Open the Arduino IDE, go to Sketch > Include Library > Manage Libraries...
     - Search for "TinyGPS++" in the library manager, select it from the results, and click Install.
   * Create a new project in the Arduino IDE (File > New Sketch) with the name `GPS_tracker.ino`.
   * Add the following code to your sketch:
```cpp
#include <SoftwareSerial.h>
#include <TinyGPS++.h>

// Define pins for GPS module
const int gpsTXPin = 2;
const int gpsRXPin = 3;

// Define pins for cellular module
const int cellTXPin = 4;
const int cellRXPin = 5;

// Create a SoftwareSerial object to connect to the GPS module
SoftwareSerial gpsSerial(gpsTXPin, gpsRXPin);

// Create a TinyGPS++ object to parse GPS data
TinyGPSPlus gps;

void setup() {
  // Initialize serial connections for both modules
  Serial.begin(9600);
  gpsSerial.begin(9600);

  // Initialize cellular module
  cellTXPin = digitalRead(cellTXPin);
  cellRXPin = digitalRead(cellRXPin);
}

void loop() {
  // Read GPS data from the GPS module
  while (gpsSerial.available()) {
    char c = gpsSerial.read();
    if (gps.encode(c)) {
      Serial.print(F("Location: "));
      Serial.print(gps.location.lat(), 6);
      Serial.print(F(", "));
      Serial.print(gps.location.lng(), 6);
      Serial.println();
    }
  }

  // Send GPS data to the cellular module
  String gpsData = "AT+GPSLOC=" + String(gps.location.lat()) + "," + String(gps.location.lng());
  cellTXPin.write(gpsData.c_str());

  delay(1000);
}
```
   * Upload the code to your Arduino board using the USB cable and the Arduino IDE.

5. Functional Testing:
   * Power on the system.
   * Open the Serial Monitor in the Arduino IDE (Tools > Serial Monitor).
   * The GPS device should send its location data every second, and you will see it displayed in the serial monitor.

6. Integration with Cellular Module (Optional):
   * If your cellular module is configured to send SMS or HTTP requests, you can modify the code above to include these functions.
   * This will allow you to track the GPS device's location remotely using SMS or HTTP requests.

Note: The above instructions are for a basic GPS tracking device. For more advanced features such as cellular communication and remote monitoring, additional hardware and software components may be required.

 Hardware Requirements:
   - Arduino Uno Board (Cost: $30)
   - GPS Module (Cost: $10-15)  (Example: Adafruit Ultimate GPS HMC5883L 3-axis Compass & GPS Breakout  - $14.95)
   - SIM900A GSM/GPRS Shield for Arduino (Cost: $25-30)
   - Breadboard and jumper wires
   - Power source (Battery or USB)
2. Software Requirements:
   - Arduino IDE (Free Download) 
   - Google Maps API Key (Free, but needs a project to be created on Google Cloud Console)

3. Step-by-Step Instructions:

Step 1: Connect GPS Module to Arduino Board

* Connect VCC of GPS module to the digital pin 5V on Arduino
* Connect GND of GPS module to the digital ground pin on Arduino
* Connect RX of GPS module to the digital pin TX (Arduino) and TX of GPS module to the digital pin RX (Arduino)

Step 2: Upload GPS Tracking Sketch

1. Download the necessary libraries for GPS tracking:
   - Download the "TinyGPS" library from here: https://github.com/mikaloha/TinyGPS 
   - Download the "Sim900a" library from here: https://github.com/simonmonk/SIM900A
2. Copy and paste the following code into your Arduino IDE:

```c
#include <TinyGPS.h>
#include <SoftwareSerial.h>

#define RXPin 0 // Pin for GPS RX signal
#define TXPin 1 // Pin for GPS TX signal

SoftwareSerial gpsSerial(RXPin, TXPin);

void setup()
{
  Serial.begin(9600);
  gpsSerial.begin(4800);
}

void loop()
{
  while (gpsSerial.available() > 0)
    if (gpsSerial.read() == 0x1B)
      break;

  if (gpsSerial.available() > 0)
    Serial.write(gpsSerial.read());
}
```

3. Upload the code to your Arduino board.

Step 3: Connect SIM900A GSM/GPRS Shield for Arduino

* Connect VCC of SIM900A shield to the digital pin 5V on Arduino
* Connect GND of SIM900A shield to the digital ground pin on Arduino
* Connect TX of SIM900A shield to the digital pin RX (Arduino) and RX of SIM900A shield to the digital pin TX (Arduino)

Step 4: Upload GPS Tracking Sketch with SMS Feature

1. Download the necessary libraries for SMS:
   - Download the "SoftwareSerial" library from here: https://github.com/PaulStoffregen/SoftwareSerial
2. Copy and paste the following code into your Arduino IDE:

```c
#include <TinyGPS.h>
#include <SoftwareSerial.h>

#define RXPin 0 // Pin for GPS RX signal
#define TXPin 1 // Pin for GPS TX signal

SoftwareSerial gpsSerial(RXPin, TXPin);
SoftwareSerial SIM900A SerialSIM900(7,8); 

void setup()
{
  Serial.begin(9600);
  gpsSerial.begin(4800);
  SerialSIM900.begin(19200);
}

void loop()
{
  while (gpsSerial.available() > 0)
    if (gpsSerial.read() == 0x1B)
      break;

  if (gpsSerial.available() > 0)
    Serial.write(gpsSerial.read());

  if(SerialSIM900.available()>0)
  {
    char data = SerialSIM900.read();
    if(data == 'G') // Check for 'G' character
    {
      sendSMS(); // Send SMS on receiving 'G'
    }
  }
}

void sendSMS()
{
  String smsText = "+[Your Phone Number]: [GPS Latitude], [GPS Longitude]";
  SIM900A.print("AT+CMGF=1");   // Set the SMS mode to text mode
  delay(100);
  SIM900A.println("AT+CMGS=\"" + "+[Your Phone Number]\""); // Send SMS to your phone number
  delay(100);
  SIM900A.print(smsText); // Send the SMS text
  delay(100);
  SIM900A.println(CHAR(26)); // End of message
}
```

3. Upload the code to your Arduino board.

Step 5: Create a Google Maps API Key

1. Go to https://console.cloud.google.com/
2. Click on "Select a project"
3. Click on "New Project" and fill in the required details
4. Enable the Google Maps JavaScript API and Google Maps Geolocation API
5. Get an API key from the API dashboard
6. In your Arduino code, replace `[Your API Key]` with your actual API key

Step 6: Integrate GPS Tracking Device with Google Maps

1. Use a library like "TinyGPS" to extract GPS data from the GPS module
2. Send the GPS data to a server using HTTP or HTTPS request
3. Use the Google Maps API to display the GPS location on a map

Here's an example code snippet:

```c
